Subject: flash in cs education

Last week I sent a question about uses of Flash in CS Education.
Here is what I learned.  I have attached the individual examples
below, listed approximately in chronological order of their arrival.

None stated a particular textbook, several said they are still
looking for a good textbook to use in their classes.  There were
several others who were interested in the topic too. Enjoy.


Lakshmi Prayaga
University of West Florida
Uses it in Intro to game programming Course and finds it extreemly
good. Students are very motivated because it is an integrated
environment meaning you can both design and write the code in 1
place. Also uses it in summer camps which is again very successful.

Timothy T. Yuen (Doctoral Candidate)
The University of Texas at Austin
Has taught Flash/ActionScript to children as a way to teach game
making.  It seemed to work well with the children since visualization
of the code (through the symbols) was pretty inherent in the
projects. Studying uses of Flash to teach OO, for more details on his
dissertation see http://www.csnub.com.

Scott Leutenegger
University at Denver
Paper at SIGCSE 2007 (A games first approach to teaching introductory
programming) about his use of Flash and ActionScript in his "Games
First" CS1 class. http://doi.acm.org/10.1145/1227310.1227352. Another
publication at CCSC in 2006. His website is available at http://
www.cs.du.edu/~leut/.

Bill Hochstettler
Franklin University
Franklin University is using it in a course on animation for the web.

Ursula Wolz
The College of New Jersey
ActionScript is used in their introductory course CSC 101 which is
cross-listed with Interactive Multimedia as IMM 120. The course is
called "Introduction to Interactive Computing."

John Barr
Ithaca College
Ithaca College offers a course for non-majors on Flash development
including actionscript.  They are considering a gaming minor which
would include this course.

Eric Sedgwick
DePaul University
They just started doing this, using ActionScript for intro
programming for their Interactive Multimedia program.


