Manuel -- I somehow missed your original posting on this. Thank you
for the summary!

In the Software Engineering course I taught at UT Austin from 1997 to
2006, many teams used Flash to create software to meet the needs of
their clients (the required project was often educational software).
The nature of this SWE class required each team to figure out the
skills they needed to complete their projects and how to best acquire
those skills if they did not have them. Unfortunately, the course
site has been deactivated but I will plan to search through and list
out resources teams recommended as helpful while they came up to
speed with Flash.

A seemingly tricky issue is how to make Flash accessible. A former
student of mine, Thea Eaton, has founded a company to create
accessible software for pre-college settings. During a panel on
accessibility that I organized for the Austin chapter of IEEE Women
in Engineering, Thea explained how to make Flash accessible. Her talk
combined content and presentation by means of an accessible Flash
show. Thea's presentation, as well as information from the other
panelists, are at the URL http://austin-wie.org/minutes/minutes-
centex-wie-060920.htm

